{{About|the Islamic concept of wisdom||Hikma (disambiguation)}}

{{Contains Arabic text|section}}
'''''Hikmah''''' (also '''''Hikmat''''', {{lang-ar|حكمة}}, ''{{transl|ar|ḥikma}}'', literally [[wisdom]], philosophy; rationale, underlying reason,<ref name="wehr">{{cite book|last1=Wehr|first1=Hans|editor1-last=Cowan|editor1-first=J. Milton|title=A DIctionary of Modern Written Arabic, Arabic-English|date=1961|publisher=MacDonald & Evans Ltd.|page=197|edition=1980}}</ref>) is a concept in [[Islamic philosophy]] and law.

[[Mulla Sadra]] defined ''hikmah'' as "coming to know the essence of beings as they really are" or as "a man's becoming an intellectual world corresponding to the objective world".<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Cooper|first=John|title=Mulla Sadra (Sadr al-Din Muhammad al-Shirazi) (1571/2-1640)|editor-first=Edward|editor-last=Craig|encyclopedia=[[Routledge Encyclopedia of Philosophy]]|volume=6|pages=595–599|location=London; New York|publisher=Routledge|year=1998|isbn=978-0415073103|via=Islamic Philosophy Online|url=http://www.muslimphilosophy.com/ip/rep/H027.htm}}</ref> Various Islamic commentaries describe hikmah as "to know the best of things by way of the best of sciences ...",<ref>{{cite book|last=Ibn Mandhur|title=Lisan al-'Arab|pages=15/30}}</ref> having experience,<ref>{{cite book|last=al-Asma'i|title=as-Sihah|pages=5/1901}}</ref> using "justice in judging", "knowledge of the reality of things",<ref>{{cite book|title=Taj al-'Arus'|pages=8/353}}</ref> "that which prevents ignorance,"<ref>{{cite book|last=Ibn Faris's|title=Mu'jam Maqayis al-Lughah|pages=2/91}}</ref> putting "things in their proper places, assigning them to their proper status", etc.<ref>{{cite book|title=Taysir al-Karim ar-Rahman|pages=1/233}}</ref> According to [[Ibn al-Qayyim]], the highest and most exclusive of the three levels of hikmah are "reserved for the [[Sahabah|Companions]] over the rest of the [[Ummah]], and it is the highest level that the [Islamic] scholars can reach."{{cn|date=November 2016}}

As a term of ''[[fiqh]]'' (Islamic jurisprudence), [[Taqi Usmani]] describes it as meaning "the wisdom and the philosophy taken into account by the legislator while framing the [Islamic] law or the benefit intended to be drawn by [the law's] enforcement". One Dr Dipertua calls it "the objectives and wisdom" as "prescribed by Shariah".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Asyraf Wajdi Bin Dato’ Hj. Dusuki Yang Dipertua|title=The Challenge of Realizing Maqasid Shariah in Islamic Finance|url=http://www.iais.org.my/e/attach/2015/maqasid2015/pdf/keynote3_ppt.pdf|website=iais.org.my|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref>

Usmani gives as an example the secular law for traffic lights, where ''illat'' (another term of ''fiqh'' meaning "the basic feature of a transaction that causes relevant law to be applied") is obedience to stopping at red lights, and ''hikmah'' is traffic safety -- avoiding vehicle and pedestrian collisions.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Usmani |first1=Muhammad Taqi |title=The Historic Judgment on Interest Delivered in the Supreme Court of Pakistan |publisher=albalagh.net |location=Karachi, Pakistan|url=http://www.albalagh.net/Islamic_economics/riba_judgement.pdf |date=December 1999 |ref=MTUHJI1999 |}}, paras 119-120</ref> 

